The difference between constructor-injection and field-injection is that with field-injection, the injected component is NOT available (==&gt; null) **during the constructor**, it will be available directly after the constructor, for example in a method annotated with `@PostConstruct` or at any later stage **as long as the constructor has finished**.

```
// example of Vaadin View class using field injection

@PageTitle(&quot;User Access&quot;)
@Route(value = &quot;user-access&quot;, layout = MainLayout.class)
public class UserAccessView extends Div {

@Autowired
private AccountRoleRepositoryService accountRoleRepositoryService;  

public UserAccessView() {
    // accountRoleRepositoryService is null at this point
}}

@PostConstruct
public void methodThatRunsAfterConstructorCompleted() {
    for(AccountRole ar : accountRoleRepositoryService.findAll()){
        System.out.println(&quot;role: &quot;+ar.getRole());
    }
}
```

HOWEVER:  
It sounds to me like you ask this because you want to instantiate your UserAccessView Class yourself (-&gt; `new UserAccessView()`). I don&#39;t know why you want that, but be aware that ANY injection will not work in this case. Even field injection like above. Injection using `@Autowired` or `@Inject` ONLY work when the class gets instantiated automatically by the underlying framework -&gt; spring components, vaadin views, ..

In my opinion, there is no real upside to using field-injection over constructor-injection. Because usually you want the injected component to be available during the constructor.

